Sure, here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

``` 
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    ifstream infile("text.txt");
    int count = 0;

    while (infile >> line) {
        if (line.find("word") != string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    cout << count << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program uses the `ifstream` class to open the text file and read its lines. It then uses the `while` loop to iterate over each line and check if the specified word is found in the line. If it is, the `count` variable is++)++)++)++)++) set to the number of occurrences of the word. Finally, the program prints the count to the console.

Note that this is just a simple example, and in a real program you would likely want to add error handling and input validation to the program to ensure that the file is valid and the word is not present in the file in unexpected ways.
